{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488550"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:46:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:46:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"476"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/476"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.07,0.56,0.23,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107640"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/476"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90071"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43012"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107640"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with pain in her right knee that started overnight. She has a history of hypertension, controlled congestive cardiac failure, chronic kidney disease and gout. She takes perindopril, furosemide, and metoprolol. She feels unwell and can barely walk because the knee is so swollen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 102/min, blood pressure 145/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 100% on room air, and temperature 37.5\u00b0C. The right knee is swollen with overlying skin that is flushed and warm, and the joint is tender to touch. An arthrocentesis is conducted. The synovial fluid culture is negative, and negatively birefringent crystals are present in the synovial fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allopurinol","Paracetamol","Prednisolone","Indomethacin","Codeine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute gout flare affecting her right knee. The diagnosis is confirmed by the presence of negatively birefringent crystals in the synovial fluid and negative culture results, which help rule out septic arthritis. Management of an acute gout flare focuses on controlling the inflammatory response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial therapy for this patient. Steroids (oral, intramuscular, or intra-articular) are effective for acute gout flares and are particularly suitable for patients with chronic kidney disease, where NSAIDs are contraindicated. A typical regimen would be prednisolone 15-30mg daily until symptoms resolve (typically 3-5 days), followed by a short taper. Given this patient\u0027s comorbidities, particularly chronic kidney disease, prednisolone offers the best balance of efficacy and safety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndomethacin\u003C/strong\u003E and other NSAIDs are commonly used first-line for acute gout flares due to their anti-inflammatory properties. However, they are contraindicated in patients with significant renal impairment, as in this case. NSAIDs can worsen kidney function and may also exacerbate heart failure, making them unsuitable for this patient. Additionally, using indomethacin would complete the \u0027triple whammy\u0027 effect, as the patient is already on an ACE inhibitor (perindopril) and a diuretic (furosemide), which together with an NSAID significantly increases the risk of acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllopurinol\u003C/strong\u003E is a urate-lowering therapy used for long-term management of gout to prevent recurrent attacks. While current guidelines indicate that allopurinol can be started during an acute gout flare (contrary to previous recommendations), the priority in acute management remains controlling the inflammatory symptoms. Allopurinol does not provide immediate relief of acute symptoms and would typically be considered after addressing the acute inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E may provide some pain relief but has minimal anti-inflammatory effect. While it could be used as an adjunct therapy, it is insufficient as monotherapy for an acute gout flare where controlling inflammation is the primary goal. Paracetamol alone would not adequately address the underlying inflammatory process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECodeine\u003C/strong\u003E and other opioids may help with pain control but, like paracetamol, do not address the underlying inflammation. Additionally, codeine has potential side effects including constipation, nausea, and sedation, which can be particularly problematic in elderly patients. It would not be an appropriate first-line therapy for acute gout.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["First line management for an acute gout flare is NSAIDs, steroids or colchicine.","Steroids (oral, IM or intra-articular injection) are a good option for an acute gout flare in a patient with severe renal impairment.","While allopurinol can be started during an acute gout attack, the priority is managing acute symptoms with anti-inflammatory therapy."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Gout (Internet). 2019. Access at: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=gout\u0026guidelineName=Rheumatology\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e176.","Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Colchicine (Internet). AMH. 2021. Access at: https://amhonline-amh-net-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/chapters/rheumatological-drugs/drugs-gout/other-drugs-gout/colchicine.","Robinson, P \u0026 Stamp, L. The management of gout: much has changed. RACGP, Vol 45, No 5, May 2016, Pages 299-302. Access at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/may/the-management-of-gout-much-has-changed/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"476"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90071"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T14:52:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T14:54:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"476"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107640"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,